entry.title: First Project
entry.summary:
Project Benson¶

Introduction¶

This is my first blog post and my first project for the 2016 Fall Cohort of Metis Data Science bootcamp. Our assignment was to parse MTA turnstile data to determine which stations are busiest and whatever further information we could discover from the data.

MTA Turnstile Data File Formats¶

The MTA turnstile data was available in two different text formats (one before 2014, the other afterwards).

Each separate file on the website corresponds to one week's worth of turnstile data (333 total at time of project).

All data was parsed and processed with pandas (with the exception of a few weeks that could not be parsed correctly at first attempt).

Scraping and Parsing Data¶

I created a script to download all of the turnstile data files and process them into a usable format. This process was successful for all but 6 of the weekly log files (04-14-12, 04-21-12, 04-28-12, 07-07-12, 08-18-12, and 11/22/2014) which with a little bit more time to troubleshoot could also be included for future work.

Data in the files is present as cumuluative entries and exits per turnstile. There are numerous errors within the data (random spikes and dropouts), so spikes in the data were removed and timepoints where the change in entries or exits was negative or greater than the 95%ile for that turnstile were set to 0 or the 95%ile respectively.

Looking at the data...¶

Take an example station (e.g. 1st ave L train). Plotting multiple weeks of data demonstrates the overall trend of greater traffic on weekdays with a dropoff on weekends. A few outliers are noted (including one Friday with zero traffic, either an error or station closure).

Global trends can be seen in the mean station traffic by weekday (with a minimum of traffic on Sunday and slightly more on Saturday). Surprisingly there is a slight decrease in traffic on Monday relative to the rest of the week, although this may be related to Monday holidays (which could be explored in future work).

Overall traffic also demonstrates a seasonal trend, with decreased traffic during summer months (Jul and Aug) and winter (Nov-Jan). Further work could explore the relationship between these trends and likely rationales for decreased subway traffic like school vacations (i.e. summer, thanksgiving, and winter).

Looking at the overall trend over all the data (binned by week), there is an obvious seasonal pattern to mean station traffic. The effect of outlier events is also evident, for although some of the minima represent missing data from my processed dataset (red marks), the green line represents the complete closure of the subway system during Hurrican Sandy.

Out[5]:

Distribution of total ridership among different stations¶

Looking at the histogram of traffic by station, most stations have relatively low amounts of traffic. A few very busy stations are responsible for a large percentage of the overall traffic in the system (at least in terms of entries and exits, transfers would not be captured by this data).

The stations with the greatest overall traffic include the usual suspects (Grand Central, Penn Station, Times Square), as well as additional stops along the overworked 456 line.

Certain stations are more popular on weekends than others, and one quick way to look at this is to take the ratio of weekend to weekday traffic. Not surprisingly, baseball stadiums have a lot of people traveling to and from their respective stations on weekends, relative to most stations in the subway system.

Conclusion¶

This was just an introductory project for me for this course, and there are numerous additional directions I would take this dataset if I had more time. I may add to this post with maps generated from the geopandas module when I have time.
